arXiv:2508.02795v1 Announce Type: new Abstract: Recent measurements of astrophysical neutrinos have expanded our understanding of their nature and origin. However, very little is still known about the astrophysical $ ar{
u}:
u$ ratio. The only prior measurement is the recent, single Glashow event seen by IceCube. Understanding the astrophysical $ ar{
u}:
u$ ratio has a bearing on multiple questions, including the astrophysical spectral shape and neutrino production mechanisms. This analysis uses a new approach to measuring the astrophysical muon $ ar{
u}:
u$ ratio at various energies. It uses inelasticity, the fraction of the initial neutrino energy carried away by the hadronic shower. Inelasticity probes the $ ar{
u}:
u$ ratio due to the fact that at energies below roughly 100 TeV, valence quarks dominate in deep inelastic scattering interactions, leading to different neutrino and antineutrino inelasticities and cross-sections. We use 10.3 years of IceCube data consisting of starting tracks at energies between 1 TeV and 1 PeV with a self-veto selection that enhances astrophysical event purity in the down-going direction. Based on this sample and analysis method, we present the first measurement of the astrophysical $ ar{
u}:
u$ ratio at sub-PeV energies.

arXiv:2312.03984v4 Announce Type: replace-cross Abstract: Many polyatomic astrophysical plasmas are compressible and out of chemical and thermal equilibrium, introducing a bulk viscosity into the plasma via the internal degrees of freedom of the molecular composition, directly impacting the decay of compressible modes, $\mathbf{v}_{\parallel}(\mathbf{k})$. This is especially important for small-scale, turbulent dynamo processes in the interstellar medium, which are known to be sensitive to the effects of compression. To control the viscous properties of $\mathbf{v}_{\parallel}(\mathbf{k})$, we perform trans-sonic, visco-resistive dynamo simulations with additional bulk viscosity $
u_{m bulk}$, deriving a new $
u_{m bulk}$ Reynolds number $m{Re}_{m bulk}$, and viscous Prandtl number $m{P}
u \equiv m{Re}_{m bulk} / m{Re}_{m shear}$, where $m{Re}_{m shear}$ is the shear viscosity Reynolds number. We derive a framework for decomposing $E_{m mag}$ growth rates into incompressible and compressible terms via orthogonal tensor decompositions of $
abla\otimes\mathbf{v}$, where $\mathbf{v}$ is the fluid velocity. We find that $\mathbf{v}_{\parallel}(\mathbf{k})$ play a dual role, growing and decaying $E_{m mag}$, and that field-line stretching is the main driver of growth, even in compressible dynamos. In the absence of $
u_{m bulk}$ ($m{P}
u 	o \infty$), $\mathbf{v}_{\parallel}(\mathbf{k})$ pile up on small-scales, creating a spectral bottleneck, which disappears for $m{P}
u \approx 1$. (abridged). We emphasize the importance of further understanding the role of $
u_{m bulk}$ in compressible astrophysical plasmas, which we estimate could be as strong as the shear viscosity in the cold ISM, and highlight that compressible direct numerical simulations without bulk viscosity have unresolved compressible mode dissipation scales.
